>Arctics are adapted to harsh winters and starvation. As a part of living in the far north, Arctics can sometimes go days without food in winter. To circumvent this, Arctics hoard (cache) their food and store their body fat.
>Red and arctic foxes have a less than stellar relationship in the wild where their territories overlap. Oftentimes reds will kill and eat arctics, largely due to the latter’s smaller size.
>Arctics form complex dens are deep and often have multiple entrances. They can last for decades and house generations of fox families. The red fox Wikipedia page mentions nothing about this so I can only assume it’s unique to arctics.
>There’s also some smaller things, like some unique physical differences that Arctics have that serve to retain heat such as overall smaller facial features and more rounded ears. They also have unique vocalizations.
>Wikipedia also mentions their roundness as being a specific adaptation.

This had once stumped me as well so here's some useful information

Catholics, ever since Saint Thomas Aquinas was canonized, by virtue of canonization believe that On Being and Essence (worth a read might I add), which, while technically answers the question on Mongols being human, the Mongols, at least to 13th century Italians were literal horse people as in Anthros. Aquinas concluded that if it was in the resemblance and spirit of a man, it has a soul, and thus be Christian.
The wording is quite particular, being that of spirit, which assumes a mortal soul unlike that of a demon.

Modern Thomism has this to say on the matter of souls, take this as you will:
>Thomists define the soul as the substantial form of living beings. Thus, plants have "vegetative souls," animals have "sensitive souls," while human beings alone have "intellectual" – rational and immortal – souls -Dubray (1909)

Take the Catholic School of thought as you will.

As for the Orthodox/ Oriental Churches, Thomism is mostly rejected and the idea of a soul is tied to the idea of humanity, though this may change after Constantinople falls in 1453 depending on the Muscovite's official stance on Anthros

The Protestants can be summed up along the larger branches.
>Lutherans- Depends on the national/regional church in question, considering that the Church of Denmark would likely preside over a large number of both humans and anthros I image they would continue Thomism, whereas some in Germany, the U.S and insular churches would adopt a "their flavor only" and abandon Thomism.
>Baptists- Given that baptism is the most important idea in their sect, I image it would focus on who, can be baptized, i.e must have hair that can be wet or skin that can shed the sin, it could vary wildly.
>Calvinists- Like anyone should listen to these heretics.

Islam wouldn't give a shit as long as they weren't "Haram" anthros I imagine, given its historical apathy towards ethnicity.

No one else matters really

I really want to put together an infographic for furries to help them understand how to finish projects. I think a lot are autistic/artistic and both those traits aren't conducive to finishing complex projects. So far I got
>Set milestones. Mile stones are goals you can reach within the project. IE finish all character art, finish gameplay mechanics, choose an engine,
>Make a plan. Stick to the plan.
>Set an end date. Take it seriously.
>Set dates to review the project. Typically around the time you complete a milestone.
>When reviewing, look if you're going to make milestones and dates on time. Also review on what things would have slowed your progress and remove that.
>Often, you will find yourself doing the same work over again to be more efficient or effective.
>Always be mindful of what the customer wants in the product and how to maximize the value of the product.

That's what I did for my book, anyway.

It makes my autistic brain itch, but only because I used to work for a managed service provider (IT mercenaries, essentially) that had lots of contracts with big pharmaceutical companies. The tl;dr is that the lab boys find all manner of interesting stuff all the time, but first they spend a year or so doing Ames Tests on bacteria to see whether it's a mutagen. Then, if the Ames Test doesn't show the new drug is instant cancer juice, it's a couple of years of tests on rats and mice to see if it gives them cancer, establish LD50, establish a rough therapeutic dosage range, etc. Then, if the rodents don't all die immediately--which happens sometimes--they go to the FDA and file for permission to start human testing. The approval process can take several years, and the FDA can and does require re-running all the tests with different batches of mice, etc. If the FDA says yes, then it's 10+ years of experimental tests on human "volunteers." When I say "volunteers" I mean the kind of people who answer ads for free insulin, if they're testing a new kind of synthetic insulin. It's mostly winos and methheads with chronic medical conditions and relatively few normal people. Once these tests elapse, all the test data goes to the FDA, who may sit on it for a decade or two before deciding whether or not to approve the new drug. There are experimental drugs out there that have been in the pipeline since the Ford Administration. It takes decades and costs billions, with a B, of US dollars to get from "bright guy in the lab has an idea" to "here's your new antibiotic from BigBioCo." Bright guy in the lab may have died of old age before the doctors can start writing prescriptions for his idea. But it only bugs me because I have this information in my head, so...
